  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation reduces a
logical-select form: %r = select i1 %cmp, i1 %cmpeq, i1 false into just %cmpeq.
The original IR is poison-safe because %cmpeq (an icmp marked 'samesign') is only
evaluated for the result if %cmp is true. After transformation, %cmpeq's poison
propagates unconditionally. Alive2 shows a counterexample: x = -128, y = 0. Here,
%cmpeq is poison (violated 'samesign' promise), but original result is the
defined constant false because %cmp is false. The transformed IR incorrectly
yields poison.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nInstCombine logs show the select being
visited, then foldAndOrOfICmpsWithConstEq applied, producing an 'and %cmpeq,
true'. That binary 'and' is then simplified to return %cmpeq directly.
Critically, the transformation path swapped the operands and invoked
foldAndOrOfICmpsWithConstEq with IsLogical set to false (see foldAndOrOfICmps
lines 3366-3373). With IsLogical=false the helper builds a bitwise AND rather
than a logical (short-circuit) AND, forcing unconditional evaluation of both
operands. The comment claims it is safe to drop logical semantics because \"both
operands are used on the LHS\". That assumption is wrong for a select pattern
'select %cmp, %cmpeq, false'. Only %cmp is always evaluated; %cmpeq is
conditionally used.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe bug comes from
foldAndOrOfICmps (lines 3366-3373). After attempting the fold in logical form
(LHS,RHS), it retries with swapped operands but deliberately forces
IsLogical=false, converting short-circuit logical AND/OR into bitwise AND/OR.
This loses poison safety when the equality compare (Cmp0) may produce poison but
was previously guarded by the other compare in a select. The 'samesign' attribute
on an icmp is a promise; violating it yields poison. Eliminating the guard
changes semantics. The code's justification about both operands' poison
propagating is incorrect for select-form logical ops.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s):\nEdit lines 3369-3373 in InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp to preserve logical
semantics when the original operation was logical (IsLogical == true). Instead of
hard-coding IsLogical=false for the swapped attempt, pass through the original
IsLogical flag (or conditionally skip the second attempt when logical). This
maintains short-circuiting and prevents unconditional evaluation (and hence
propagation) of a potentially poison-producing compare. Revised block:\n//
Preserve logical (short-circuit) semantics for select-form booleans.\n// Swapping
operands may enable the pattern; do not force bitwise form\n// because that can
incorrectly expose poison from a guarded icmp (e.g. 'samesign').\nif (Value *V =
foldAndOrOfICmpsWithConstEq(RHS, LHS, IsAnd, IsLogical, Builder, Q))\n  return
V;\nRemove the misleading comment about safe conversion to bitwise.\n\nThis
change confines folding to a poison-safe form for selects while retaining
existing optimization opportunities when the original was a true bitwise AND/OR
(IsLogical==false).\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy keeping IsLogical unchanged in the
swapped fold attempt, we avoid transforming a short-circuit logical select into a
bitwise operation that evaluates (and propagates poison from) the 'samesign' icmp
unconditionally. This restores correctness for cases where the equality compare
may be poison unless guarded, fixing the miscompile demonstrated by Alive2
without broadly disabling the optimization.\n",
